The HS Chromebook distribution was much better today. We serviced 315 students in 4 hours. Last Friday, we saw 348 students in 8 hours. David Turner

post_text:
I want to offer my deepest apologies for the length of time it took us to hand out Chromebooks, Textbooks, and Schedules today. We serviced 348 families today and the wait was just too long. I was impressed with how many families graciously accepted my apology as they received their items. That is a testament to the quality community members Marshall High School is fortunate to serve.

We are making changes to our delivery process on Monday, August 24 from 2:00 p.m. to 6:00 p.m.

While people are waiting outside, MHS staff will hand out their technology agreement form so parents can review and sign it before entering the building. This will greatly reduce the wait time, since this was the main culprit of our log jam. Taking the student picture, logging on to a computer, and getting books and schedules was a reasonable wait time and does not require any adjustments.

Again, thank you parents for being so patient and we promise to do a better job on Monday, August 24 from 2:00 p.m. to 6:00 p.m.

Sincerely,

David Turner
Marshall High School Principal

post_text: ATHLETES! REQUIRED TO PARTICIPATE NEXT WEEK! TURN IN COMPLETED FORM TO COACH AT FIRST PRACTICE! For the 2020-21 school year the MHSAA pre-participation sports physical requirement will be waived for students in any grade who received a valid physical for sports during the 2019-20 school year (one completed on or after April 15, 2019). Students and their parents/guardians will be required to complete the two-page MHSAA ANNUAL SPORTS HEALTH QUESTIONNAIRE (click below to find a link to the questionnaire). These must be signed by student and parent/guardian and kept on file in the school. Students who did not receive a sports physical in the 2019-20 school year or later must have a valid physical examination form on file. Parents can choose to still have their child complete the regular physical exam. Both forms can be found by clicking through to the page in the link below.

You have the power to choose.
At MPS, we know there is not just ONE right answer to what school should look like this fall; that's why we are offering our 2,700 students and their families the option to return to the physical building or to select a virtual-only option. If you are ready to make the decision to enroll in virtual-only, you can use the link below. If you would like to hear more about your options, tune in to the July 20th board meeting at 7:00p. post_text: The Marshall Athletic Boosters (MAB) have decided, along with Marshall Country Club, to move forward with the 2020 Redhawk Open on Saturday August 15th. At this time there is uncertainty about the upcoming school year and sports. We know sports will return, we are just not sure when. We want to continue our fundraising efforts but are aware of the financial hardships the pandemic has created. We are making some adjustments to our 2020-21 Sponsorship Campaign. Things could change between now and August 15th and we will be flexible and adhere to the health and safety guidelines provided by the State of Michigan. Click the link below to read more.

Beginning on Monday (5/4), Marshall MS and HS band students will have the opportunity to participate in virtual clinics led by members of "The President's Own" United States Marine Band, from Washington, DC. These are some of the finest musicians in the world that will be working with our students over the next two weeks.

‚ÄúThe President‚Äôs Own‚Äù United States Marine Band‚Äôs mission is to perform for the President of the United States and the Commandant of the Marine Corps. Founded in 1798 by an Act of Congress, the Marine Band is America‚Äôs oldest continuously active professional musical organization. Today, ‚ÄúThe President‚Äôs Own‚Äù is celebrated for its role at the White House and its dynamic public performances, which total more than 500 annually.

Attached is a document with information and specific times. Feel free to share!

Questions? Contact Jeremy Root at jroot@marshallpublicschools.org

post_text:
‚ÄúMarshall High School administrators and senior class sponsors are busy planning ways to recognize and celebrate the accomplishments of our 2020 graduates before this school year ends. We wish to produce a video to be premiered by the end of May that represents each graduate, his or her next steps after high school, speeches from two chosen senior class representatives, and the official Board acceptance of high school completion for the Class of 2020.

We also plan to have a program printed and sent home to each graduate as a keepsake. Our hope and expectation is that this recognition will be a great placeholder until such time we can convene an in-person, traditional commencement ceremony for our graduates and their families.

Please join us in rising above these challenging times of the COVID-19 pandemic to celebrate this milestone in the lives of our Marshall Public School graduates and their families.‚Äù

Dr. Davis

post_text:
Marshall Public Schools Families,

Marshall Public Schools is committed to providing sack breakfast and lunches for our families. These will be available free of charge to anyone who is 18 years old or younger. We will be providing these sack breakfast and lunches Monday through Friday starting Tuesday, March 17 through Friday, April 3. Below is a list of pick-up and drop off locations. Our transportation department will be providing the drop offs. Please have students waiting at these locations and looking for our busses. See attached images for further details.

Should you need any further information please feel free to contact Jeremy Yettaw, Food Service Director at jyettaw@marshallpublicschools.org or myself at bjones@marshallpublicschools.org.

Sincerely,
Becky Jones
Director of Business Operations

Eight students from the Albion community competed in the Battle Creek NAACP 2020 Heritage Quiz Bowl over the weekend. The group consisted of six students from Marshall High School, one from Parma Western High School, and one from Concord High School.

The students successfully captured first place in the High School category! The Albion/Marshall team was composed of two qualifying teams.
Team 1 students - Ayo Olapade, Marshall Nicholson, Belevia Stovall, and Aliyah Roberts.
Team 2 - Aruila Wade, Grace Sobaski, EmmyLou Christensen, and Jamiyah Funderbeg.

Team 2 won the final round and first place which includes a monetary prize for the school. The team was coached by Edmon Mann and Temple Stovall.

post_text:
A HUGE THANK YOU for all of your support in facilitating the recent League of Women Voters - Voter Registration Event at Marshall High School. üá∫üá≤üá∫üá≤üá∫üá≤

We registered 116 students, 67 of whom are eligible to vote in the March 10, 2020 Presidential Primary.

This is a phenomenal success rate. Across the country, high school voter registration drives typically result in 30 - 40% of high school seniors registering to vote (about the average for voter turnout for 18 - 24 year olds in 2018). Marshall High School safely exceeded the average by a wide margin.

As a reminder, Michigan.gov/vote is a great resource to help voters:

‚úÖ View your Sample Ballot for the upcoming election
‚úÖ Track the status of your Absentee Ballot
‚úÖ Verify your Voter Registration Information and locate their polling place

And, Vote411.org provides non-partisan information on candidates and their views and ballot initiatives prior to each election.
text:
A HUGE THANK YOU for all of your support in facilitating the recent League of Women Voters - Voter Registration Event at Marshall High School. üá∫üá≤üá∫üá≤üá∫üá≤

We registered 116 students, 67 of whom are eligible to vote in the March 10, 2020 Presidential Primary.

This is a phenomenal success rate. Across the country, high school voter registration drives typically result in 30 - 40% of high school seniors registering to vote (about the average for voter turnout for 18 - 24 year olds in 2018). Marshall High School safely exceeded the average by a wide margin.

As a reminder, Michigan.gov/vote is a great resource to help voters:

‚úÖ View your Sample Ballot for the upcoming election
‚úÖ Track the status of your Absentee Ballot
‚úÖ Verify your Voter Registration Information and locate their polling place

And, Vote411.org provides non-partisan information on candidates and their views and ballot initiatives prior to each election.
